2. Draba hirta L.

As D. mayellanica is thus not the Draba hirta of Lm- NAEUS, one might be tempted to conclude it to be some gla- brous form of Draba rupestrz's R. BR. — LINDBLOM‚ (ll. c. c.). But this plant is not his D. hirta either. The type specimen, which I have had the opportunity of seeing in the herbarium of LINNAEUS in the Linnean Society in London, corresponds completely with the diagnosis and description l. l. c. c.‚ the word ›>hirta›> being interpreted to mean: »hairy with simple hairs». As far as I could see, the hairs were only cilia of about one mm. in length. The rather robust stem had only one leaf under the lowest pedicel.
